Perhaps we should move those demos to a folder like "old and doesn't work anymore dont bother testing" :)
It is fine to have old examples, but if we do, we can't run tests on new distributions without constantly having those old variants failing.
Perhaps we will have the same problem with the old Potts "temperature" versus the new "FluctuationAmplitude". Most of the demos still use "temperature". I suspect that "temperature" is still used in a few places in the documentation. Tweditt++ (3.7.9 distro) still uses "temperature" for newly created models.

column13: Volume parameters initialized from XML if not specified in steppable
column20:
Per JAG's request: CellG instance members targetVolume and lambdaVolume should be initialized based on XML. To accommodate setting in steppable start methods, I added on-the-fly initialization at first call to changeEnergy to populate instances with values according to whatever is specified in XML by type (if anything). So the precedence is steppable.start() assignments by cell > XML spec by type > default = 0 for both members.
The only limitation is that if nonzero member values are specified in XML for a type and both are set to zero during steppable start for a CellG instance of that type, the members of the instance will be overwritten according to the XML during the first step. However, this seems like an unlikely scenario.

column21:
I am not sure if this makes sense. What if you create new cells in the simulation. Will you be also initializing targetVolume and lambdaVolume in this situation?
Another issue, even if you do initialization what does it buy you? If you are using global settings from XML then by definition you will not be calling energy function that uses cell->targetVolume. In fact you confuse users who would think that volume plugin is indeed using cell->targetVolume.
Another point what if I change XML while simulation runs (known as steering) To be consistent I would also need to rerun  initialize_target_volume.
If I were a user and I saw cell->targetVolume=28 but plugin calculated energies as if targetVolume was 15 then I would be confused and I can easily create such situation with CC3D. I really think it is better to keep current code and not introduce extra logic that is hard-to-maintain

column21:
I was thinking the past few days, why do we even have global, cell type, cell id as different behaviors in c++?
We could read from XML and write into the cell object instead of keeping a list. This way we only need one energy function and the attributes will always be available in python without any xml-reading function.
How does this sound? I don't see this breaking anything but I could be wrong

If I've understood this correctly, then there would only be the cell data parameters for constraint and coefficient, and no type-specific list maintained by the plugin. Is that correct?
If so, I'm inclined to agree in the sense that computations should be done by accessing parameters by cell, rather than by using cell type as a key to a global list. In my opinion, much of the strength of the framework is being able to edit parameters by cell in Python. I would only keep the parameter data by type in the plugin as a reference for memory purposes (not computer memory) so that, say, a cell's parameters could be reset to the defined parameters by cell type on-the-fly.
But in general, I think that parameter operations should be done at the level of the cell, and not the type. Granted, it requires more memory, but I think it's worth it.

I think that given our backlog we could postpone further discussion of volume plugin . I really do not think this is that important. I think what would be more important is to think about more comprehensive overhaul of our specifications. I am in favor of per-cell definitions of parameters . This would work in some cases but keep in mind that we also have interactions and those are best recorded in some type of "global" object. Anyway as far as this particular PR I suggest we do not include it . If we want to do something radical we need to do it in a coordinated effort and address issues like that for all plugins. column13: Fixed lost secretion in array swapping for ReactionDiffusionSolverFE
Fixed lost secretion in array swapping for ReactionDiffusionSolverFE
column21: Current implementation in the solver prohibits usage without scaling, in which case diffusion is first executed, and then secretion. Before this fix, the solver places diffusion calculations in t+1, secretion terms in t, and then implements the array swap. This is how secretion is currently getting lost. The fix places secretion updates into t+1 before the array swap, producing expected behavior in all of my tests.

Previously, it was

Secretion: getDirect->setDirect

Fixes two issues in GUI-less mode

Extra fields weren't being written to file
start was called once in main loop when not restarting, and then called again whether beginning or restarting a simulation. Along with not being appropriate for restarting a simulation, this can potentially cause an error depending on user-defined steppables (e.g., calling start twice that creates an extra field when running a new simulation)

column20:
Please checkout branch on your machine and run few simulations with FPP plugin to make sure the behavior is reasonable
This is PR addresses several issues

it improves rendering of fpp links
it changes how we compute distance in the fpp plugin to obey boundary conditions. Previous code was not correct in this regard. However, when the length of the link was much smaller than "avg lattice size" (as it was in most simulations) this did not create an issue. The issue occurred when e.g. you have link in the z direction and its length is > 0.5 of the z dimension.
Changes to invariant_distance/invariant_distance_vector to respect boundary conditions. Same motivation , problems, and impact as in 2)

Link rendering can still be improved but overall this version is much better and than what we had before
Issues addressed in this PR:
#350
#347
#312

column20:
Highlights:

New general class: DerivedProperty
DerivedProperty members return a value like a member variable according to a member function evaluation defined on the parent class in C++ and Python
A member function defining the value of a DerivedProperty is restricted to information intrinsic to its class
New interface file collects all Python implementations and includes a macro that reduces implementation to a single line per DerivedProperty
Implementations in this PR: CellG pressure, surface tension and cluster surface tension

Notes on future work: waiting on link class definition to define a link tension

column20:
This PR extends workflows using the CC3D Python API to support programmatic rendering of spatial data
Highlights

Front-end dev includes classes that wrap data rendering from single simulations and multiple simulations in parallel
Back-end dev improves general usage of rendering infrastructure
A simple demo shows a fully Python-based computing workflow, from simulation execution to rendering of spatial data

Idea for future work

Design and generate screenshot specifications using a simple stand-alone GUI and user data
Add a feature to Player to export screenshot specifications based on current graphics to a user-specified location
Paraview integration?

column20:
Overhaul of focal point plasticity
Summary

New link classes now form the basis of link computations
Three link classes are defined (regular, internal and anchor links) and derived from a base class with an interface for link-specific model specification.
Link inventory classes function like the cell inventory, but for each type of link; each link inventory is derived from a base class through which most link management is defined.
New Python and wrapped C++ infrastructure simplifies link creation/destruction and provides convenience functions and iterators for links by inventory and cell.
Maintains all current functionality of focal point plasticity.
Supports multi-threading to the same extend as the current implementation.
Performance in single- and multi-threaded simulations is approximately the same as the current implementation.

column21:
Adding boolean networks is great. We needed them for a long time and I know other users have been implementing them by hand. I admit I have not gone through entire code but I have few questions:

is there an option to compile CC3D without MaBoSS? Let's say the user faces compilation issues on their operating system but they do not need boolean network. Can we somehow disable compilation? BTW this is the only reason I am asking this question
Would it be possible to use  similar approach as we did with roadrunner/ antimony integration? I.e. we provide "hooks" for integrating MaBoSS but pyMaBoSS is compiled separately from CC3D? What I am hinting here is possibility to include in CC3D only code that is written by us and have all 3rd party additions be compiled separately and integrated "at the Python level"


I've revised the description of the PR according to recent development. The extensions PR allows for selective installation of the MaBoSS extension, and the built-in support implemented in this PR handles when the extension is missing.
@CompuCell3D I completely agree with you about migrating all 3rd party code out, and only include built-in supporting features here. I'm planning to migrate the RoadRunner and Antimony integrations to the extensions repo as simple metapackages, for now, and we can think about a tighter integration when opportune. I would also like to do similar restructuring for Player and Twedit.

It is actually much simpler GUI-based configuration process then before - you select variable, number etc that you want to scan (highlight it in twedit++) and then right-click and choose an option to add it to parameter scan and then the GUI will show up. The same process can be used to remove a given parameter from being scanned. Pretty simple workflow overall

CellType Plugin automatically assigns the lowest available integer to each type ID that is not specified via CC3DML.

column20:
This PR replaces the BasicUtils module with a new plugin manager, exception, random number generators and other minor features.
Features

Added CC3DException for error handling.
Added ExtraMembers for dynamically adding members to class definitions.
Added RandomNumberGenerators with optional random number generators, including the current generator and Mersenne Twister. Mersenne Twister is the default, and the current generator is named "Legacy".
Promoted PluginManager to full implementation with new plugin approach.

@tjsego thanks. Let me try that. I think the Azure/Travis/Github actions build scripts need to be in the same repository because the builds need to be triggered by an event that happens to the repository. For example a pull request. Also, the build reports are incorporated into the repo.
But I'm not 100% sure. Let me research this a little.
@tjsego I also requested an Azure Pipeline account for this repo. But Azure didn't give me that authorization yet. Because I'm an outside contributor I'm not sure whether they will give it to me.
Would it help if we applied for the authorization to use Azure? We can certainly do it . If you can point us to the right forms we would be happy to go through with it

Here is the organization I've created.
https://dev.azure.com/CompuCell3D
Added both TJ and James (IU user names) to the organization. I'm trying to make you the owners of the organization.
Here is the form we need to submit.
https://aka.ms/azpipelines-parallelism-request
I got the authorization. Now I'm checking the pipeline.

@CompuCell3D @tjsego  The build pipeline is ready. I think now the question is where should we keep the YML file. From the research I've done so far, I couldn't find a way to keep the script in a separate repository.

HI @supunkamburugamuve : if we are going to use azure pipeline to run integration tests I think it makes sense to keep it within current repository. A question for you : what is the main intent of this azure pipeline?
I think the immediate goals are to compile the project and run the integration tests.
This makes sense. Do you think the yml is ready to go? if so I can approve and merge it
@CompuCell3D the integration tests are failing at the moment. But the script is working. Do we need to do the pull request to the develop branch?
Hi @supunkamburugamuve  I would say develop would be better. Lets change the PR and we will merge it. What is failing in the regression tests?
@CompuCell3D did the pull request against the develop branch. Closing this one.

column20:
Reworks how build targets are handled. Aliases to build targets reduce the clutter from platform-dependent shared/static library selection. For example, instead of PublicUtilitiesShared vs. PublicUtilitiesStatic, there’s now one alias cc3d::PublicUtilities.
Adds relocatability and some light CMake config stuff to facilitate incorporate cc3d as a dependency in other builds.
Removes Player and Twedit. See CompuCell3D/cc3d-player5#1 for Player migration and CompuCell3D/cc3d-twedit5#1 for Twedit.
Removes PREFIX_CC3D. Installed packages now locate resources by introspection. As a consequence, import cc3d works in any environment in which CC3D is installed without any further environment setup.

TODO

Update license to MIT
Update package versioning in conda recipe when distributing.
